In article <PCL.93Dec29150033@foo.oucs.ox.ac.uk>,
Paul C Leyland <pcl@foo.oucs.ox.ac.uk> wrote:
>Even if I use *truly* random offsets for each character of a Caesar
>cipher, or xor-values for the traditional computer implementation, and
>even if I *never* repeat them, as is required for a OTP, I *still* have to
>be careful that my random numbers span a large enough range.

Right.  More precisely, you need one randomizing bit per message-bit.

>I've thrown a coin and either added or subtracted 1 from each alphabetic
>character in an English-language message.

This has one randomizing bit per six message-bits, so it's not a one-time
pad system.

